image:image.image:title: Rakali (water rat) Â© Tracy Oliver
image:image.image:caption:
Rakali (water rat)
The image has been provided as part of the Rakali Community Survey. This new citizen science project is designed to improve knowledge of this elusive native rodent whose current distribution, habitat needs and threats are poorly known. As a top-order predator, rakali may be useful indicators of healthy waterways, and this project will also aim to influence better management of rivers and wetlands in Western Australia.

image:image.image:title: 5 dead water rats
image:image.image:caption: The rakali is also often caught unintentionally in traps and nets like these five killed in a single crab trap at cherry pools in Victoria. The trap owner didn't seem to be particularly concerned.
